// int data type
int age = 25; // This line declares an integer variable named 'age' and initializes it with the value 25. The 'int' data type is used to store whole numbers without decimal points. In this case, 'age' represents a person's age, which is typically expressed as a whole number.

// double data type
double pi = 3.14159; // This line declares a double variable named 'pi' and initializes it with the value 3.14159. The 'double' data type is used to store floating-point numbers, which are numbers that can have decimal points. In this case, 'pi' represents the mathematical constant π, which is approximately equal to 3.14159.

// char data type
//char grade = 'A'; // This line declares a char variable named 'grade' and initializes
//it with the value 'A'. The 'char' data type is used to store a single character, which can be a letter, digit, or symbol. In this case, 'grade' represents a letter grade, which is commonly used in educational settings to indicate a student's performance.

// bool data type // This line declares a boolean variable named 'isStudent' and initializes it with the value true. The 'bool' data type is used to store boolean values, which can be either true or false. In this case, 'isStudent' indicates whether a person is a student or not, with true meaning they are a student and false meaning they are not.
